{"name": "pynormaliz-inequalities", "metadata": {"name": "PyNormaliz-inequalities", "version": "0.1.2", "classifiers": [], "home_page": null, "license": "MIT License", "documentation_url": null, "dependencies": ["PyNormaliz"], "summary": "A Python package for interacting with PyNormaliz using inequalities.", "upload_time": 1734475884}, "documentation": ["# PyNormaliz_inequalities\n\n[Normaliz](https://github.com/Normaliz/Normaliz) is a tool for various computations in discrete convex geometry. In particular it supports computations in polytopes and polyhedra specified by a system of linear inequalities.\nFor example, it allows to compute the Hilbert or Ehrhart series of a polytope or polyhedron, and thereby count the number of integer points in it.\n\nIt is possible to interact with Normaliz using the Python package [PyNormaliz](https://github.com/Normaliz/PyNormaliz), but the interface requires users to specify inequalities in a vector format. \nThis package provides a more convenient interface for specifying inequalities in a natural format, and includes utility functions for interacting with PyNormaliz.\n\n## Installation\n\nNormaliz and PyNormaliz must be installed on your system to use this package. You can install these packages using the following commands:\n\n```sh\ngit clone https://github.com/Normaliz/Normaliz.git\ncd Normaliz\n./install_normaliz.sh\n./install_pynormaliz.sh\n```\n\nTo install this package, use pip:\n\n```sh\npip install PyNormaliz_inequalities\n```\n\n## Usage\n\nThe main point of the package is to allow users to specify inequalities in a natural format.\nThe main components are `Variable`s that can be combined into `Expression`s and `Inequality`s, which can be collected into an `InequalitySystem`, which can then be passed to PyNormaliz.\n\n### Example: Basic Usage\n\nLet's count the number of integer pairs `(a,b)` with `a + b = n` that satisfy the inequalities `a >= 0`, `b >= 0`, and `a + b >= 1`, as a function of `n`.\n\n```python\nfrom PyNormaliz_inequalities import Variable, InequalitySystem, evaluate_quasipolynomial\n\na = Variable()\nb = Variable()\n\ninequalities = InequalitySystem()\ninequalities.add_inequality(a >= 0)\ninequalities.add_inequality(b >= 0)\ninequalities.add_inequality(a + b >= 1)\n\nquasipolynomial = inequalities.construct_homogeneous_cone().HilbertQuasiPolynomial()\nprint([evaluate_quasipolynomial(quasipolynomial, n) for n in range(10)])\n```\n\n## Explanation\n\nThe `PyNormaliz_inequalities` package provides a convenient interface to PyNormaliz, allowing users to specify inequalities in a natural format. It supports creating variables, expressions, and inequalities, and converting them to vector representations suitable for PyNormaliz. The package also includes functionality to construct homogeneous cones and compute Hilbert quasi-polynomials.\n\nThe main components of the package are:\n\n- `Variable`: Represents a variable in an inequality.\n- `Expression`: Represents a linear expression involving variables.\n- `Inequality`: Represents an inequality involving expressions.\n- `InequalitySystem`: Manages a system of inequalities and provides methods to interact with PyNormaliz.\n\nThe package also includes utility functions for converting inequalities to vector representations and evaluating quasi-polynomials.\n"], "modules": [{"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [], "classes": [], "exports": [{"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.evaluate_quasipolynomial", "xref": {"fqname": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.evaluate_quasipolynomial", "project": null}}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.Expression", "xref": {"fqname": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.Expression", "project": null}}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.Inequality", "xref": {"fqname": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.Inequality", "project": null}}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.InequalitySystem", "xref": {"fqname": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.InequalitySystem", "project": null}}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.Variable", "xref": {"fqname": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.Variable", "project": null}}]}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.evaluate_quasipolynomial", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "qp", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "n", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["Evaluates a quasipolynomial at a given integer value.\n\nArgs:\n    qp (list): The quasipolynomial represented as a list of lists.\n    n (int): The integer value at which to evaluate the quasipolynomial.\n\nReturns:\n    int: The evaluated value of the quasipolynomial.", "###################", "### Example use ###", "###################"]}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.better", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "perm", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "x", "type": null, "default": null}, {"name": "y", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}], "variables": [{"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.A", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.perms", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.profile", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.inequalities", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.margin", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.ineq1", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.ineq2", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.ineq", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequalities.polyhedron", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "PyNormaliz_inequalities.inequaliti